Filesystems — the layer that turns blocks into files.

So you've got a partition. But a partition is just a slice of raw bytes; it can't hold files yet. To actually store files, you need a filesystem laid down inside it. The filesystem is the layout that says: here's the index of all the files, here's where each file's data lives on disk, and here are the permissions for each. Without a filesystem, a partition is just empty space.

Let's meet the common ones. ext4 is the default on most distributions: stable, mature, well-understood, a great general-purpose choice. xfs is the default on Red Hat systems and excels with large files and high parallelism, but note, it cannot be shrunk. btrfs, the b-tree filesystem, brings snapshots, subvolumes, and built-in RAID, and it's the default on openSUSE and Fedora Workstation. Then there's vfat and its successor exfat, used for universal compatibility on USB sticks and EFI partitions, but they have no concept of permissions. And tmpfs is a RAM-backed filesystem used for things like slash-tmp and slash-run; it vanishes on reboot. For exam purposes, know ext4 deeply and xfs well; the rest are situational.

To create a filesystem, you use mkfs, with the type as a suffix. So sudo mkfs-dot-ext4 on a partition formats it as ext4, and you can add dash-capital-L to give it a label. sudo mkfs-dot-xfs formats it as XFS. And here's the warning that bears repeating: mkfs destroys everything on the target. There's no "format but keep my data" option; formatting is inherently destructive. The target also has to be unmounted, and mkfs will refuse otherwise.

Finally, checking and repairing: that's fsck. It runs automatically at boot for most filesystems, so you'll usually only run it by hand after a crash or when you suspect corruption. But there's a critical rule: the filesystem must be unmounted before you run fsck. Running it on a live, mounted filesystem can corrupt it, which is exactly why the boot-time check happens before the filesystem is mounted. One exception to remember: for XFS, fsck-dot-xfs does nothing at all; XFS uses a separate tool called xfs-underscore-repair instead.
